  "text": "The Firefox NSS library implements comprehensive TLS/SSL protocol support across multiple specialized files in security/nss/lib/ssl/:\n\n1. **ssl3con.c** - The core TLS implementation file handling SSL 3.0 through TLS 1.2. It implements record processing through ssl3_UnprotectRecord(), cipher suite negotiation and configuration, master secret and key derivation (ssl3_ComputeMasterSecret, ssl3_DeriveConnectionKeys), and handshake message handling (ssl3_HandleClientHelloPart2, ssl3_HandleServerHelloPart2). This file contains the critical cipherSuites table that defines all supported cipher suites and their properties.\n\n2. **tls13con.c** - Implements TLS 1.3-specific protocol handling including the new handshake flow. Key functions include tls13_SetCipherSpec() for cipher configuration, tls13_SendServerHelloSequence() for server-side handshake, tls13_ComputeHandshakeSecrets() and tls13_ComputeApplicationSecrets() for the HKDF-based key derivation, and tls13_UnprotectRecord() for record protection. It handles the stateless server, 0-RTT, post-handshake authentication, and session resumption mechanisms introduced in TLS 1.3.\n\n3. **dtlscon.c** - Implements DTLS (Datagram TLS) protocol support with UDP-specific handling. It includes version mapping functions (dtls_TLSVersionToDTLSVersion, dtls_DTLSVersionToTLSVersion) to bridge DTLS and TLS versions, retransmission timer management (dtls_StartRetransmitTimer, dtls_RetransmitTimerExpiredCb), and MTU-based fragmentation handling. The file maintains compatibility with DTLS 1.0, 1.2, and 1.3.\n\n4. **ssl3ecc.c** - Specialized implementation of ECC (Elliptic Curve Cryptography) cipher suite operations. Contains functions like ssl_NamedGroup2ECParams() and ssl_ECPubKey2NamedGroup() for EC parameter handling, and ssl3_ComputeECDHKeyHash() for ECDH key exchange verification. This file was separated from ssl3con.c to organize EC-specific cryptographic operations.\n\n5. **sslexp.h** - Header file declaring experimental SSL APIs that are not yet stable or standardized. It provides the SSL_EXPERIMENTAL_API() macro framework for accessing experimental features, extension hook interfaces for custom extension handling, and capability negotiation APIs. This allows applications to test new features while maintaining API stability guarantees for standard functions.\n\nThese five files form the core of Firefox's TLS protocol implementation, with ssl3con.c handling SSL 3.0/TLS 1.0-1.2, tls13con.c handling TLS 1.3, dtlscon.c handling datagram variants, ssl3ecc.c handling elliptic curve operations, and sslexp.h providing experimental API access."
